Crude Oil Volatility Falls as Futures Drop on Bernanke Comments

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-08-26T17:36:26Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-26/crude-oil-volatility-falls-as-futures-drop-on-bernanke-comments.html
Oil options volatility decreased as
the underlying futures dropped in  New York  after Federal Reserve
Chairman  Ben S. Bernanke  failed to announce new stimulus in an
address at  Jackson Hole ,  Wyoming .  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
October, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options prices, was 43.4 percent at 1 p.m. in New York,
down from 45.4 percent yesterday. Options volatility was 48
percent a week ago.  Oil for October delivery fell 38 cents, or 0.5 percent, to
$84.92 a barrel at 12:37 p.m. on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange . Prices have fallen 7.1 percent this year.  The most active contract in electronic trading today was
October $75 puts, with 2,375 lots changing hands as of 1:35 p.m.
in New York. The options fell 15 cents to $1.01 a barrel.
October $70 puts, the next-most active option, retreated 11
cents to 52 cents with 1,852 lots trading. One contract covers
1,000 barrels of crude.  Eight of the 10 most-active options today were October or
November puts with strike prices ranging from $50 to $80 a
barrel. Puts outnumbered calls almost three to one in electronic
trading on the Nymex.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occur the next business day.  October $75 puts were the most active options traded in the
previous session, with 4,130 lots changing hands. They rose 7
cents to $1.16 a barrel. The next-most active options, December
$70 puts, gained 10 cents to $2.32 a barrel on volume of 3,920.  Open interest was highest for December $100 calls with
49,237 contracts. Next were December $70 puts with 43,741 and
December $80 puts with 42,850.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in Dallas at 
